intro: Henslowia frutescens var. subquinquenervia, commonly known as the broad-leaved henslowia, is a flowering plant native to the southeastern United States. It is a member of the Apiaceae family, characterized by its aromatic foliage and umbellate inflorescence. The plant features compound leaves with five to seven leaflets, often with a distinct venation pattern. Its flowers are small and white, arranged in flat-topped clusters, and it produces small, angular fruits. This variety is distinguished by its broader leaves and more pronounced venation compared to the typical form of Henslowia frutescens.
